Hi @Anton-Shutik, thanks for contributing.
After reviewing your PR, I realize that there is potentially a conflict between two different use cases. Your PR makes the ResourceRelatedField generate valid links that point to the non-nested url for the related object in to-one relationships. But it introduces a problem with using nested routes.

Nested routes are used for to-many relationships, for example `/entries/<entry_pk>/comments` would be the route for all comments that have a foreign key to the entry with pk `<entry_pk>`. That behavior appears to be unchanged by your PR. 

However, examples in the JSON API spec use nested routes for to-one relationship links as well; note that in [this example](http://jsonapi.org/format/#document-resource-object-linkage) that in the author link, `"http://example.com/articles/1/author"`, the id 1 in that url is the id of the article, not of the related person, whose id is 9.

I think flat routes in relationship links may actually violate the JSON API spec:
>Additionally, a related resource link MUST NOT change because its relationship's content changes.

(See [Related Resource Links](http://jsonapi.org/format/#document-resource-object-related-resource-links))

With the flat route, the relationship link will change if the relationship is changed, i.e. if the foreign key is updated to point at a different object. With a nested route, `/articles/1/author` will always point to the author of article 1, even if the relationship is changed to point at a different person object.

In the project @jsenecal and I are working on, we are using a lot of nested routes, with the help of [drf-nested-routers](https://github.com/alanjds/drf-nested-routers). For example, an Organization may have a parent organization, which is represented by a foreign key. We have a route that maps the url `organizations/<pk>/parent` to the detail view for the parent of organization <pk>.

With the develop branch, the `parent` relationship object on `organizations/2` looks like this:
```json
      "parent": {
        "data": {
          "type": "organization",
          "id": "1"
        },
        "links": {
          "self": "http://localhost:8000/api/contacts/organizations/2/relationships/parent",
          "related": "http://localhost:8000/api/contacts/organizations/2/parent"
        }
      }
```
Even if this organization is sold to a different parent organization, the related link will be the same: `organizations/2/parent`.

With this PR it looks like this:
```json
      "parent": {
        "data": {
          "type": "organization",
          "id": "1"
        },
        "links": {
          "self": "http://localhost:8000/api/contacts/organizations/2/relationships/parent",
          "related": "http://localhost:8000/api/contacts/organizations/1/parent"
        }
      }
```

As you can see, the related link in the second version is now pointing to the parent of organiation 1, rather than the parent of organization 2.

